This paper is about supervised learning of neural networks, which is a topic that falls under the broad category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper specifically focuses on lifted network formulations, which are energy models for discriminatively trained neural networks. This could also fall under artificial intelligence (cs.AI) since energy-based models are commonly used in AI. The paper also mentions using contrastive loss for training, which is a technique commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper discusses the use of massively parallel hardware, which could fall under the category of system and control (cs.SD).
